            <p>A <strong>blood chemistry analyzer</strong> is a laboratory instrument used to measure chemical concentrations in blood serum or plasma. If you wonder <strong>how does a blood chemistry analyzer work</strong>, it typically utilizes centrifugation to separate plasma, mixes the fluid with specific chemical reagents, and uses light absorption (spectrophotometry) or electrochemistry to measure levels of glucose, lipids, kidney markers, and liver enzymes.</p>
